 origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Tyndale was born in 1440, in Hockwold cum Wilton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas Tyndale, was 26 and his mother, Margaret Yelverton, was 16. He married Dame Mary Montfort in 1478, in Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1488, in his hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1440–1488":"1440–1488","1443–1497":"1443–1497","1444–1513":"1444–1513","–1521":"–1521","–Female":"Surnud","1440–1496":"1440–1496","1475–1529":"1475–1529","1476–1539":"1476–1539","1478–1540":"1478–1540","–Male":"Surnud","1415–Male":"1415–Surnud","1425–1513":"1425–1513","1440":"1440","Abt 1478":"umbes 1478","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1513":"1513","1478":"1478","1488":"1488","1521":"1521","1444":"1444","1476":"1476","1443":"1443","1475":"1475","1497":"1497","1540":"1540","1496":"1496","1529":"1529","1539":"1539","Hockwold, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Hockwold, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hockwold cum Wilton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Hockwold cum Wilton, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England","Overton with Shipton, Yorkshire, England":"Overton with Shipton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1440–1488":"1440–1488","1443–1497":"1443–1497","1444–1513":"1444–1513","–1521":"–1521","–Female":"Kuollut","1440–1496":"1440–1496","1475–1529":"1475–1529","1476–1539":"1476–1539","1